    {
      "step_id": "6f118e2b",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "CYP2D6 inhibitors commonly present:\n- A **basic center protonated at physiological pH** that can form a key ionic interaction (often with an acidic residue in the active site, commonly discussed as **Asp301** in CYP2D6).\n- One or more **hydrophobic/aromatic regions** to occupy lipophilic pockets.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:47:29.533633+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "2b2e7864",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**This molecule:**\n- **Hydrophobic/aromatic bulk is present** (tetralin + phenyl), which supports **active-site occupancy** and potential competitive inhibition.\n- **Basicity is the weak point**:\n  - **Amides are non-basic**.\n  - The **imine N** is typically only weakly basic, and conjugation to adjacent carbonyl-containing nitrogens further suppresses protonation.\n  - The **aniline** is only weakly basic; at pH 7.4 it may be partially protonated but often not strongly enough to mimic the classic \u201ccharged tertiary amine\u201d CYP2D6 inhibitor motif.\n- Net effect: likely **weaker CYP2D6 inhibition** than classic cationic inhibitors; could still be a **moderate/weak inhibitor** via hydrophobic binding and H-bonding, but less likely to be a strong inhibitor.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:47:29.533646+00:00"
    },
    {
